Utenbogardus and Festus to them, that they might know from them what had been done in this conference at Delft, and what hopes shone forth of concord being entered on. Festus sincerely and without disguise (nu- deque) related what had been done, and declared that hope of peace shone forth, only provided the Remon- strants would openly declare their opinion on the articles delivered to them. Utenbogardus, by courtly craftiness, had procured that he should be heard alone, Festus being absent, that he might the more freely propose the things which he thought would serve his own purpose. And when he had odiously traduced the proceedings of the rest of the pastors, as the persons who, by the demand of a declaration, (which yet before the eonference he him- self had promised,) endeavoured to bring a new inquisition into the churches, and one by no means to be endured, obtained that the same persons should be forbidden any more to demand this declaration from the Remonstrants, and moreover, that it should at the same time be enjoined on them to explain more at large in writing their counsel on the best way of peace, and concerning the conditions by which they thought that atoleration should be circum- scribod.
